    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1251122411" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1251122411" />
    <a title="Tanya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15698555-tanya"><img alt="Tanya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602837639p2/15698555.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1251122411?book_show_action=true">Apr 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tanya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tanya" href="/user/show/15698555-tanya">Tanya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/24927805-the-boys-from-brazil">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1251122411" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15752714715813502457">I <i>adore</i> Ira Levin. His stories are all killer, no filler, with the most ludicrous, far-fetched seeds of ideas at their root... brought alive so <i>convincingly</i>. His boundary-pushing imagination chills me to the bone, and <i>The Stepford Wives</i> and <i>Rosemary&apos;s Baby</i> are among my all-time favorite books. <i>The Boys From Brazil</i> is a novel that defies categorization—it&apos;s part speculative fiction, part thriller, part sci-fi, all based on real historic figures, and one hell of a wild ride.<br/><br/>The year is 1974, and Y</span>
  <span id="freeText15752714715813502457" style="display:none">I <i>adore</i> Ira Levin. His stories are all killer, no filler, with the most ludicrous, far-fetched seeds of ideas at their root... brought alive so <i>convincingly</i>. His boundary-pushing imagination chills me to the bone, and <i>The Stepford Wives</i> and <i>Rosemary's Baby</i> are among my all-time favorite books. <i>The Boys From Brazil</i> is a novel that defies categorization—it's part speculative fiction, part thriller, part sci-fi, all based on real historic figures, and one hell of a wild ride.<br /><br />The year is 1974, and Yakov Liebermann, a Nazi hunter loosely based on Simon Wiesenthal, receives a phone call from a young man in Brazil who claims to have overheard a plot to bring about the Fourth Reich. Dr. Josef Mengele, the Angel of Death, who cruelly experimented on identical twins and people with physical abnormalities (such as heterochromia and dwarfism) to study genetics and heredity in order to "prove" the theory of Aryan supremacy during his time at Auschwitz, is sending six former SS officers out into the world on a strange assignment: To kill 94 men (all 65 year-old civil servants with younger wives) on or around a certain date over a span of a couple of years. Liebermann suspects a prank, but when some of the facts check out, he begins to investigate, and when Mengele realizes that his old nemesis is on the right track to figure out his plan, a dangerous and suspenseful game of cat-and-mouse ensues.<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>"The Fourth Reich is coming—not just a German Reich but a pan-Aryan one."</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />Something that must've been especially chilling at the time of publication is the inclusion of real characters: Dr. Mengele, arguably the most-wanted Nazi war criminal, was still alive and in hiding in South America, and substantial rewards for his capture were still being offered both by governments and independent groups and individuals. He died three years after the book came out, but his remains weren't exhumed until the mid-80's, and his identity confirmed beyond any lingering doubts by DNA testing in 1992.<br /><br />Levin could rightly be called the master of excellent, nail-biting suspense-novels (and his screen-play-like writing make them perfect for being adapted to the screen—as this particular one was, as well, starring two greats, Gregory Peck and Laurence Olivier), and he successfully keeps the mission's goal secret for the better part of the novel. What makes it disturbing is how prescient it was: The sci-fi premise was scientifically <i>imaginable</i> in the 70's, but nowhere near close to being scientifically <i>possible</i>—today it's an entirely different story, and adds a terrifying dimension to the recurring "it can't happen <i>here</i>", or "it can't happen <i>again</i>" discourse, especially when you add the world-wide shift towards right-wing politics we've been experiencing.<br /><br /> <i>
  <blockquote>"Two factors are necessary for a resurgence of Nazism (...) a worsening of social conditions till they approximate those of the early thirties and the emergence of a Hitler-like leader."</blockquote>
</i><br /><br /><i>The Boys From Brazil</i> is an incredibly gripping novel from beginning to end, and the more I reflect on it, the more I think that it's a truly timeless thriller, even though some of it reads a bit dated. Levin doesn't waste words, and knows how to put his hooks in you from the very first page. I'd recommend this book to anyone interested in <i>"what if?"</i>-scenarios, even if not too keen on sci-fi—nowadays, the premise is in the scary realm of perfectly conceivable, and the final chapter is a great example of the fine art of unsettling open endings.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15752714715813502457" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

